            <div class="clearfix text-formatted field field--name-field-body field--type-text-long field--label-hidden field__item"><h3>Introduction to watercolour illustration</h3>
<p>Sunday, July 6 from 10 am to 4 pm<br>
Ages 18 and up.<br>
Cost: $175 + tax (per person) . <a href="https://anc.ca.apm.activecommunities.com/ottawa/activity/search/detail/148801?onlineSiteId=0&amp;locale=en-US&amp;from_original_cui=true"><strong>Advance registration is required.&nbsp;</strong></a></p>
<p>Immerse yourself in a beautiful summer day at Fairfields Heritage House and learn to create nature-inspired watercolour illustrations with botanical artist and arts educator Crystal Beshara. Practice essential observational drawing techniques and gain confidence with watercolour, while painting a unique and personal nature study. This “plein air” painting workshop will take place outdoors; an indoor space and reference images will be provided in the event of inclement weather.</p>
<p>This workshop is suitable for beginners and enthusiasts alike. Materials and supplies are provided. Light refreshments will be served. Participants are invited to bring their preferred lunch from home.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Meet the artist: </strong>Crystal Beshara is an international award-winning fine artist and educator.&nbsp;For over 25 years, Crystal has taught thousands of students and led dozens of workshops across the globe, including in the USA, Greece, Ireland, Canada, France, England, and Mexico.&nbsp;Her work has been featured in international publications such as <em>International Artist Magazine, Pleinaire Salon, Fine Art Connoisseur, House &amp; Home</em>, as well as on CTV, CBC and TVO.&nbsp;Her approach to art instruction emphasizes practical skills and&nbsp;focuses on building student confidence.&nbsp;She believes that art is a powerful way to connect with others and that making art is a fundamental part of being human.&nbsp;Her teaching style aims to inspire and empower students to develop their artistic potential.&nbsp;</p>
<h4><strong><span>Notes</span></strong></h4>
<ul>
<li>This program is delivered in English.</li>
<li>This program takes place outdoors under an open-sided tent. Please check weather conditions and dress appropriately for conditions. Sunscreen and bug spray are recommended.</li>
<li>The museum grounds include grassy and uneven terrain. If you have questions or concerns regarding accessibility, please contact 613-580-9638 (Nepean Museum) or email <a href="mailto:museums@ottawa.ca">museums@ottawa.ca</a>. Additional information about accessibility can be found on the museum webpage.</li>
<li>In the event of inclement weather, the program will be moved indoors to the community room. The community room is located on the second floor of the heritage house and is accessible by stairs only.</li>
<li>Advance registration is required. Workshops with insufficient registration may be cancelled. If an alternative cannot be offered, a refund will be issued.</li>
<li>Visit the <a href="https://ottawa.ca/en/family-and-social-services/older-adults/financial-assistance#section-89551f56-14c3-4f6e-b24c-5e5072350977">Ottawa Hand in Hand</a> webpage for information on available financial supports to facilitate participation in recreation and culture programs.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
</ul>
<h3>Medicine shield workshop</h3>
<p>Sunday, July 20 from 1 pm to 2:30 pm<br>
Ages 16 and up.<br>
Cost: $75 + tax (per person) . <a href="https://anc.ca.apm.activecommunities.com/ottawa/activity/search/detail/149105?onlineSiteId=0&amp;locale=en-US&amp;from_original_cui=true"><strong>Advance registration is required.&nbsp;</strong></a></p>
<p>Led by <a href="https://www.makatew.ca/">Makatew Workshops</a>, visitors are invited to learn the significance and use of medicine shields while making their own. Participants will also discuss topics like truth and reconciliation, providing an open environment to ask questions without judgment. All skill levels, including beginners, are welcome. This workshop will take place outdoors; an indoor space will be provided in the event of inclement weather. Materials and supplies are provided. Light refreshments will be served.</p>
<p><strong>Meet the workshop facilitator:&nbsp;</strong>Marc Forgette is an Indigenous entrepreneur, educator, and speaker dedicated to fostering cultural awareness and reconciliation. As the founder of Makatew Workshops, Marc delivers hands-on experiences that provide meaningful learning opportunities for corporate, government, and institutional audiences. His expertise in Indigenous traditions, combined with his engaging approach, has earned him multiple awards, including the Think Ottawa 2024 Market Leadership Award, MPI Ottawa's Supplier of the Year, and the 2024 Influence Award. In 2025, Marc is expanding his impact with the launch of Makatew Speaks, a new division of Makatew dedicated to keynote speaking and thought leadership. Through this initiative, he will share insights on Indigenous business challenges, cultural appreciation, and the importance of Indigenous-led initiatives at conferences, corporate events, and educational institutions. With a passion for creating safe and inclusive spaces for learning, Marc is committed to building bridges between Indigenous and non-Indigenous communities through education, storytelling, and collaboration</p>
<h4><strong><span>Notes</span></strong></h4>
<ul>
<li>This program is delivered in English.</li>
<li>This program takes place outdoors under an open-sided tent. Please check weather conditions and dress appropriately for conditions. Sunscreen and bug spray are recommended.</li>
<li>The museum grounds include grassy and uneven terrain. If you have questions or concerns regarding accessibility, please contact 613-580-9638 (Nepean Museum) or email <a href="mailto:museums@ottawa.ca">museums@ottawa.ca</a>. Additional information about accessibility can be found on the museum webpage.</li>
<li>In the event of inclement weather, the program will be moved indoors to the community room. The community room is located on the second floor of the heritage house and is accessible by stairs only.</li>
<li>Advance registration is required. Workshops with insufficient registration may be cancelled. If an alternative cannot be offered, a refund will be issued.</li>
<li>Visit the <a href="https://ottawa.ca/en/family-and-social-services/older-adults/financial-assistance#section-89551f56-14c3-4f6e-b24c-5e5072350977">Ottawa Hand in Hand</a> webpage for information on available financial supports to facilitate participation in recreation and culture programs.</li>
</ul>
